'''Yohashira Shrine''' (四柱神社, Yohashira Jinja) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Ōte, Matsumoto|ja|大手 (松本市)|12=draft|12=draft}}, Matsumoto City, Nagano Prefecture. Locally, it is often referred to as "Shintō-san" due to the Shintō festival held in October. It is also commonly misread as "Shihashira."

== Overview ==
[[File:Yohashira jinja01s1920.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Shrine grounds]]
The shrine's name derives from its enshrinement of four deities: {{ill|Ame-no-Minakanushi|ja|天之御中主神|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Takamimusubi|ja|高皇産霊神|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kamimusubi|ja|神皇産霊神|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大神|1=Amaterasu|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|12=draft|12=draft}}.

{{nihongo|Hashira|柱|lit pillar}} is the counter for gods in Japanese<ref>https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E6%9F%B1</ref>

The shrine originated from the Shinto {{ill|Chūkyōin|ja|中教院|12=draft|12=draft}} established in Matsumoto, {{ill|Chikuma Prefecture|ja|筑摩県|12=draft|12=draft}}, in 1872 (Meiji 5). The Chūkyōin began enshrining the four deities in 1874 (Meiji 7). In 1879 (Meiji 12), the shrine was moved to its current location, and a shrine building was constructed, formally establishing Yohashira Shrine as a village shrine. The shrine building was destroyed in the Matsumoto Great Fire of 1888 (Meiji 21) and was rebuilt in 1924 (Taishō 13). In 1959 (Shōwa 34), Yohashira Shrine was listed as a Beppyo Shrine.

== Transportation Access ==
* 10-minute walk from {{ill|Matsumoto Station|en||ja|松本駅|12=draft|12=draft}} on the {{ill|JR|ja|JR|12=draft|12=draft}} line
* Alipico Transportation (commonly known as Matsumoto Electric Railway Bus), get off at Daimyōmachi bus stop via Matsumoto Castle, and it is immediately nearby

== Nearby Points of Interest ==
* {{ill|Matsumoto Castle|ja|松本城|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Nawate Street|ja|縄手通り商店街|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Hachijūni Bank|ja|八十二銀行|12=draft|12=draft}} Matsumoto Branch
* {{ill|Matsumoto City Timepiece Museum|ja|松本市時計博物館|12=draft|12=draft}}
== See Also ==

* [[Toyama Chukyoin]], the Chukyoin of Nagano Prefecture

